  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Data Utility Learning"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This notebooks introduces Data Utility Learning a method for improving the efficiency in computing Data Shapley values by learning to estimate the performance of a learning algorithm on unseen data combinations (i.e. subsets of the dataset). The method was described in the paper [Improving Cooperative Game Theory-Based Data Valuation Via Data Utility Learning](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2107.06336v2.pdf)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The Shapley value $\\phi_i(v)$ for data point $i$ is defined as:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\phi_i(v) = \\frac{1}{n} \\Sigma_{S \\subseteq N \\setminus \\{i\\}} \\frac{1}{\\binom{n-1}{|S|}} [v(S \\cup \\{i\\}) âˆ’ v(S)]$$\n",
    "\n",
    "For Data Utility Learning, we first start by sampling utility samples: \n",
    "\n",
    "$$S_{train} = \\{(S_i, v(S_i))\\}_{i}^{m_{train}}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where $m_{train}$ is the number of utility samples and is called the training budget.\n",
    "\n",
    "The subsets are then transformed into boolean vectors in which a $1$ at index $j$ means that the $j^{th}$ sample of the dataset is present in the subset:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$S_i \\mapsto \\{ 0, 1 \\}^{n}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "After that, we fit a regression model, $\\tilde{v}$ that we call the data utility model, on the collected samples\n",
    "and use that instead of predict the utility for the remaining samples:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\tilde{v} : \\{ 0, 1 \\}^{n} \\mapsto [0, 1] $$\n",
    "\n",
    "The main assumption here is that it is much faster to fit a model and use it to predict the utility than it is to compute the exact utility."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Imports"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "%load_ext autoreload"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "%autoreload\n",
    "%matplotlib inline\n",
    "\n",
    "import os\n",
    "import random\n",
    "from concurrent.futures import as_completed, ProcessPoolExecutor\n",
    "from warnings import simplefilter\n",
    "\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "from sklearn.datasets import load_iris\n",
    "from sklearn.neural_network import MLPRegressor\n",
    "from sklearn.svm import LinearSVC\n",
    "from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score\n",
    "from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split\n",
    "from sklearn.exceptions import ConvergenceWarning\n",
    "from tqdm.auto import tqdm\n",
    "\n",
    "from valuation.utils import Dataset, Utility, DataUtilityLearning, top_k_value_accuracy\n",
    "from valuation.shapley import get_shapley_values\n",
    "\n",
    "simplefilter(\"ignore\", category=ConvergenceWarning)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "plt.rcParams[\"figure.figsize\"] = (16, 10)\n",
    "plt.rcParams[\"font.size\"] = 15\n",
    "plt.rcParams[\"xtick.labelsize\"] = 15\n",
    "plt.rcParams[\"ytick.labelsize\"] = 15"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Constants"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "random_state = 24\n",
    "\n",
    "if os.environ.get(\"CI\"):\n",
    "    train_size = 5\n",
    "    training_budget_values = np.arange(2, 10, 2)\n",
    "    n_iterations = 1\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    train_size = 15\n",
    "    training_budget_values = np.arange(100, 8000, 250)\n",
    "    n_iterations = 10\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "mlp_kwargs = dict(\n",
    "    hidden_layer_sizes=(20, 10),\n",
    "    activation=\"relu\",\n",
    "    solver=\"adam\",\n",
    "    learning_rate_init=0.001,\n",
    "    batch_size=32,\n",
    "    max_iter=800,\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "random.seed(random_state)\n",
    "np.random.seed(random_state)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Dataset\n",
    "\n",
    "Just like in the paper, we take 15 samples from the [Iris dataset](https://scikit-learn.org/stable/auto_examples/datasets/plot_iris_dataset.html) and compute their Data Shapley values by using all the remaining samples as test set for computing the utility, which in this case is accuracy."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "X, y = load_iris(return_X_y=True)\n",
    "x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(\n",
    "    X, y, train_size=train_size, random_state=random_state, stratify=y\n",
    ")\n",
    "dataset = Dataset(x_train=x_train, y_train=y_train, x_test=x_test, y_test=y_test)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Model\n",
    "\n",
    "Also just like in the paper, we train fit a Support-Vector Classifier on the training data and we obtain an accuracy of around 92%"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "0.9259259259259259"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 7,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "model = LinearSVC()\n",
    "model.fit(x_train, y_train)\n",
    "y_pred = model.predict(x_test)\n",
    "accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Data Shapley\n",
    "\n",
    "We start by defining the utility and computing the exact Data Shapley values"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "utility = Utility(\n",
    "    model=LinearSVC(),\n",
    "    data=dataset,\n",
    "    enable_cache=False,\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "df = get_shapley_values(\n",
    "    u=utility,\n",
    "    mode=\"combinatorial_exact\",\n",
    "    progress=False,\n",
    ")\n",
    "df = df.set_index(\"data_key\")\n",
    "df = df.rename(columns={\"shapley_dval\": \"exact\"})"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Then we compute the estimates of the Data Shapley values using the DataUtilityLearning wrapper which fits, just like in the paper, a Multi-Layer Perceptron (or Fully Connected Network) on a certain number, determined by `training_budget`, of utility samples (pairs of subset of training dataset and the corresponding utility)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "application/vnd.jupyter.widget-view+json": {
       "model_id": "422847febabf499b8a133d2811106768",
       "version_major": 2,
       "version_minor": 0
      },
      "text/plain": [
       "  0%|          | 0/32 [00:00<?, ?it/s]"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "for training_budget in tqdm(training_budget_values):\n",
    "\n",
    "    def compute_shapley_values(utility: Utility, i: int):\n",
    "        utility = DataUtilityLearning(\n",
    "            u=utility, training_budget=training_budget, model=MLPRegressor(**mlp_kwargs)\n",
    "        )\n",
    "\n",
    "        dul_df = get_shapley_values(\n",
    "            u=utility,\n",
    "            mode=\"combinatorial_exact\",\n",
    "            progress=False,\n",
    "        )\n",
    "        dul_df = dul_df.set_index(\"data_key\")\n",
    "        dul_df = dul_df.rename(columns={\"shapley_dval\": f\"{training_budget}_{i}\"})\n",
    "        return dul_df\n",
    "\n",
    "    with ProcessPoolExecutor(4) as executor:\n",
    "        futures = [\n",
    "            executor.submit(compute_shapley_values, utility, i)\n",
    "            for i in range(n_iterations)\n",
    "        ]\n",
    "        for future in as_completed(futures, timeout=8 * 60):\n",
    "            dul_df = future.result()\n",
    "            df = pd.concat([df, dul_df], axis=1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "After, we compute the mean, minimum and maximum $L_1$ error for the different training budget values and plots the results"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "errors = np.zeros((len(training_budget_values), n_iterations), dtype=float)\n",
    "accuracies = np.zeros((len(training_budget_values), n_iterations), dtype=float)\n",
    "\n",
    "K = 3\n",
    "\n",
    "for i in range(len(training_budget_values)):\n",
    "    for j in range(n_iterations):\n",
    "        y_true = df[\"exact\"].values\n",
    "        y_estimated = df[f\"{training_budget_values[i]}_{j}\"].values\n",
    "        errors[i, j] = np.linalg.norm(y_true - y_estimated, ord=2)\n",
    "        accuracies[i, j] = top_k_value_accuracy(y_true, y_estimated, k=K)\n",
    "\n",
    "error_from_mean = np.linalg.norm(df[\"exact\"].values - df[\"exact\"].values.mean(), ord=2)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1152x720 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
    "ax.plot(training_budget_values, errors.mean(axis=1), \"r\", label=\"Estimated values\")\n",
    "ax.hlines(\n",
    "    error_from_mean,\n",
    "    training_budget_values.min(),\n",
    "    training_budget_values.max(),\n",
    "    \"g\",\n",
    "    label=\"Mean of Exact values\",\n",
    ")\n",
    "ax.fill_between(\n",
    "    training_budget_values,\n",
    "    errors.min(axis=1),\n",
    "    errors.max(axis=1),\n",
    "    facecolor=\"b\",\n",
    "    alpha=0.5,\n",
    ")\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel(\"$m_{train}$\")\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel(\"$L_2$ Error\")\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As can be seen, the above plot matches the plot in the paper and thus shows that the method works for estimating the Data Shapley values."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Next, we plot the accuracy for the Top 3 predicted highest value data samples. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1152x720 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
    "ax.plot(training_budget_values, accuracies.mean(axis=1), \"r\", label=\"Estimated values\")\n",
    "ax.fill_between(\n",
    "    training_budget_values,\n",
    "    accuracies.min(axis=1),\n",
    "    accuracies.max(axis=1),\n",
    "    facecolor=\"b\",\n",
    "    alpha=0.5,\n",
    ")\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel(\"$m_{train}$\")\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel(\"Average Top-K Accuracy\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "best_training_budget = training_budget_values[errors.mean(axis=1).argmin()]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1296x864 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(18, 12))\n",
    "df.plot(y=[\"exact\", f\"{best_training_budget}_{0}\"], kind=\"bar\", ax=ax)\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel(\"Index\")\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel(\"Data Shapley value\")\n",
    "plt.legend([\"Exact\", \"Estimated\"])\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Evaluation on anomalous data\n",
    "\n",
    "One interesting way to assess the Data Utility Learning approach is to corrupt some of the data and monitor how the valuation score changes. To do this, we will take the sample with the highest score and change its label."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "highest_value_index = df[\"exact\"].argmax()\n",
    "y_train_corrupted = dataset.y_train.copy()\n",
    "y_train_corrupted[highest_value_index] = (\n",
    "    y_train_corrupted[highest_value_index] + 1\n",
    ") % 3\n",
    "\n",
    "corrupted_dataset = Dataset(\n",
    "    x_train=dataset.x_train,\n",
    "    y_train=y_train_corrupted,\n",
    "    x_test=dataset.x_test,\n",
    "    y_test=dataset.y_test,\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We retrain the model on the new dataset and notice that the accuracy decreased"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "0.8296296296296296"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 17,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "model = LinearSVC()\n",
    "model.fit(x_train, y_train_corrupted)\n",
    "y_pred = model.predict(x_test)\n",
    "accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "After that, we recompute the scores of all samples using the exact method and the best training budget previously obtained and then plot the resulting scores."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "utility = Utility(\n",
    "    model=LinearSVC(),\n",
    "    data=corrupted_dataset,\n",
    "    enable_cache=False,\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "df_corrupted = get_shapley_values(\n",
    "    u=utility,\n",
    "    mode=\"combinatorial_exact\",\n",
    "    progress=False,\n",
    ")\n",
    "df_corrupted = df_corrupted.set_index(\"data_key\")\n",
    "df_corrupted = df_corrupted.rename(columns={\"shapley_dval\": \"exact\"})\n",
    "\n",
    "utility = DataUtilityLearning(\n",
    "    u=utility, training_budget=best_training_budget, model=MLPRegressor(**mlp_kwargs)\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "dul_df = get_shapley_values(\n",
    "    u=utility,\n",
    "    mode=\"combinatorial_exact\",\n",
    "    progress=False,\n",
    ")\n",
    "dul_df = dul_df.set_index(\"data_key\")\n",
    "dul_df = dul_df.rename(columns={\"shapley_dval\": \"estimated\"})\n",
    "df_corrupted = pd.concat([df_corrupted, dul_df], axis=1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1152x720 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
    "df_corrupted.plot(y=[\"exact\", \"estimated\"], kind=\"bar\", ax=ax)\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel(\"Index\")\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel(\"Data Shapley value\")\n",
    "plt.legend([\"Exact\", \"Estimated\"])\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As can be seen in the above figure, both the exact method and the approximate method agree on the fact that the sample with the corrupted label has the lowest value in the dataset."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Still, this work is preliminary and the usefulness of Data Utility Learning remains to be tested in practice.\n",
    "As can be seen in the first figure, the estimated utility's error doesn't go below the error of true utility mean.\n",
    "This can either be due to the fact that for this dataset, all the utility values are close to each other and that's why the mean\n",
    "is a better predictor or the method is not learning anything useful apart from the mean."
   ]
  }
 ],
